Here's a Java solution that uses logarithms to determine if a number is a power of three without using loops or recursion.

```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // Base cases
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }

        // Use logarithm to check if n is a power of 3
        double logValue = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return Math.floor(logValue) == logValue;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Solution solution = new Solution();

        // Test cases
        System.out.println(solution.isPowerOfThree(27));  // true
        System.out.println(solution.isPowerOfThree(0));   // false
        System.out.println(solution.isPowerOfThree(-1));  // false
    }
}
```

This solution works by using the property of logarithms that states `log(a^b) = b * log(a)`. In this case, we're using `log(n) / log(3)` to find the exponent to which 3 must be raised to get `n`. If `n` is a power of three, then `log(n) / log(3)` will be an integer. We use `Math.floor(logValue)` to get the integer part of `logValue`, and then compare it with `logValue` itself. If they're equal, then `n` is a power of three.

